\item[\cx{1}] Capacitance is the ability of a system to store an electric
  charge. The self-capacitiance of a conductor is
  $$C=q/V$$
  where $q$ is the charge held by the conductor and $V$ is the voltage.
\item[\cx{2}] A device that has constant capacitance is the \textbf{Parallel
    plate cap}. The following shows it has constant capacitance:
   $$C=\frac{\epsilon A}{d} = \frac{k\epsilon_0A}{d}\Rightarrow C\text{ is
     constant for this device},$$
   where $A$ is area, $\epsilon_0= 8.85 \times  10^{-12}\, (F/m)$ is the permittivity of space, $k$ the
   relative permittivity of a possible dielectric, $d$ is the distance between
   the parallel plates.
\
\end{itemize}

